acy in everyday religious life – such as a wavering commitment, religious negligence or weakness in faith – outside the domain of religion ‘proper.’ Straying from the Straight Path breaks with this tendency by examining how self-perceived failure is, in many cases, part and parcel of religious practice and experience. Responding to the need for comparative approaches in the face of the largely separated fields of the anthropology of Islam and Christianity, this volume gives full attention to moral failure as a constitutive and potentially energizing force in the religious lives of both Muslims and Christians in different parts of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aFailure (Psychology)xReligious aspects. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  achristianity.  acommitment.  acomparative approaches.  acrisis of faith.  acultural studies.  aethnology.  afailure and penance.  afaith and god.  agood and evil.  aholy bible.  ahuman condition.  aislam.  alife changes.  amorals and ethics.  amuslim.  apsychology and religion.  apsychology of religion.  areligious experiences.  areligious negligence.  areligious practices.  areligious studies.  areligious textbook.  aself-perceived failure.  asociology.  aspiritual conviction.  astudying religion.  atheoretical.1 aBeekers, Daan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeekers, Daan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreen, Leanne Williams, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamp, Linda van de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKloos, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l